'''Thomas Tulis''' (born 1961) is an [[United States|American]] [[photographer]] and [[Painting|painter]] living and working in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. He was born in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga]], [[Tennessee]].
Tulis lives a very simple life.<ref>Feaster, "Buh-bye Boho."</ref>
After a couple of years of college, Tulis joined the [[United States Army]]. After the army he put all of his time and efforts into his [[art]]. In 1985 he was able to open his first [[studio]] and that same year was asked to do his first exhibition.
==Work== * In ''"The South by Its Photographers"'' curated by [[Ellen Fleurov]], Tulis' work was included with many other Southern [[artist]]s including [[Shelby Lee Adams]], Walter Beckham, Debbie Fleming Caffery, [[William Christenberry]], Chip Cooper, [[William Greiner]],<ref>See Greiner's CV [http://www.williamgreiner.com/biography.asp?strNav=biography here] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718052238/http://www.williamgreiner.com/biography.asp?strNav=biography |date=2011-07-18 }}.</ref> Birney Imes and [[Melissa Springer]] among others. This exhibition traveled from the [[Birmingham Museum of Art]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama]] to [[Columbia Museum of Art]] in [[Columbia, South Carolina|Columbia]], [[South Carolina]] and the Louisiana Center for Arts and Sciences [[Baton Rouge]], [[Louisiana]]. This became an auspicious exhibition that spurred the careers of many of these Southern photographers. This exhibition was also made into a book by Susan Sipple Elliott, with an introduction by John E. Schloder, ''"The South by Its Photographers."'' * In 2003, Tulis was chosen to be part of [https://web.archive.org/web/20101226215831/http://www.wcma.org/press/03/03brouws.shtml ''Wait Until Dark''] along with [[Lewis Baltz]], Harvey Caplin, [[Todd Hido]], [[David Leventhal]], [[William Greiner]], [[Michael Kenna]], [[O. Winston Link]], [[Richard Misrach]], Jules Shulman, [[George Tice]] and [[Henry Wessel, Jr.]] The exhibition took place at The [[Williams College Museum of Art]], [[Fresno, California]]. The photographers for this exhibit were selected from the photography collection of Jay Richard DiBiaso. * In June 2002, Tulis work was selected to be part of ''"House: Ten Artists Photograph Domestic Architecture,"'' an exhibit curated by Carol John at ATHICA: [[Athens Institute for Contemporary Art]]. Evie McKenna, Rinnie Allen, [[Michael Stipe]], Carl Martin, and Mark Steinmetz were also included in this exhibition.<ref>''"House: Ten Artists Photograph Domestic Architecture"'' {{cite web |url=http://www.athica.org/exhibit.php?ID=12&action=More |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-03-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928103401/http://www.athica.org/exhibit.php?ID=12&action=More |archivedate=2007-09-28 |df= }}.</ref> * In 2004, Tulis work was chosen to be part of [https://web.archive.org/web/20060818231558/http://thecontemporary.org/pages/gallery/gallery_pastex.html ''"So Atlanta: Artists Respond to the Contemporary City"''] curated by Felicia Feaster and Helena Reckitt. The exhibition also included the work of Karen Rich Beall, Sarah Doughrety, Samm Hill, Ron Jude and [[Ohm Phanphiroj]] among others. * He has also shown at ''[[The Contemporary]]'' in Atlanta. * Tulis was represented by [[Agnes (gallery)|Agnes]] having had two solo and several group exhibitions there. Tulis was Agnes second solo exhibition.<ref>According to [http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1248/is_8_87/ai_55439581 this] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061208121206/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1248/is_8_87/ai_55439581 |date=2006-12-08 }}.</ref> * His work has been covered by ''[[Frank151]]'', ''[[Creative Loafing]]'', ''[[American Photography]]'', ''[[Aperture (magazine)|Aperture]],''<ref>No. 130, according to [http://www.thenocturnes.com/newsletter/nitenus22.htm ''Night News'' Vol. 5 No. 4].</ref> ''[[Image Geek]]'', ''[[ShotsMag]]'', ''[[The Sun (magazine)|The Sun]]'', ''[[Oxford American]]'' and ''[[Viewfinder]]''. * Tulis exhibited the now infamous, experimental art space [https://web.archive.org/web/20060813184104/http://www.shimonlindemann.com/pages/newportfolio/pages/neopostnow.htm ''Neo-Post-Now Gallery] from 1992 to 1997. The gallery was located in [[Manitowoc, Wisconsin]] and also exhibited the work of [[Matt Fink]], [[Brett Hanson]], [[Jimmy von Milwaukee]], [[Eric Lunde]], [[Alan Luft]], [[Nigel]], [[Lamar Sorrento]], James Stark, and [[Bob Watt (artist)|Bob Watt]] among many others. *His work is in numerous [[Collection (museum)|collections]] throughout the [[United States]] and [[Europe]] such as the ''[[Milwaukee Art Museum]]'', ''[[Mint Museum of Art]]'', the ''[[Museum of Modern Art]]'' the ''[[Brooklyn Museum of Art]]'', the [https://web.archive.org/web/20050506161411/http://www.pd.org/~thatguy/content_Virt01.html ''Orlando Museum of Art''], the ''[[New Orleans Museum of Art]]'' as well as the ''[[New York Public Library]]''.<ref>[http://www.oysterboyreview.com/archived/10/tulis-lunch.html Various Public Collections of Tulis work]</ref> * In 1997, Tulis was Artist in Residence at ''[[Pouch Cove]] Foundation'' located near St. John's, the capital of the [[Province of Newfoundland and Labrador]], is a self-sustaining, [[not for profit]] art retreat.
